All right, I'm coming!

23
00:07:50,436 --> 00:07:52,370
Oh, for God's sake.

24
00:07:58,878 --> 00:08:00,869
Yes?

25
00:08:04,350 --> 00:08:07,012
- What do you want?
- I--

26
00:08:09,121 --> 00:08:11,612
If you're selling something,
I'm not interested.

27
00:08:11,691 --> 00:08:13,852
I have your newspaper.

28
00:08:18,331 --> 00:08:21,061
I'm not...
I'm not selling anything.

29
00:08:21,133 --> 00:08:23,226
Then what do you want?

30
00:08:23,302 --> 00:08:25,770
It you could let me in,
I just wanna talk.

31
00:08:26,472 --> 00:08:29,032
Talk?

32
00:08:29,108 --> 00:08:32,475
I don't have anything to say
to you, boy. Good day to you.

33
00:08:32,545 --> 00:08:36,914
Bergen-Belson,
January of '43 to June '43.

34
00:08:36,983 --> 00:08:41,044
Auschwitz,
June '43 to June '44.

35
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:43,714
And then you went to Patin.

36
00:08:43,789 --> 00:08:46,257
After that, you disappeared.

37
00:08:46,325 --> 00:08:49,761
But then in 1965,
you were spotted in West Berlin.

38
00:08:51,397 --> 00:08:53,331
Listen, boy.

39
00:08:55,001 --> 00:08:57,799
I don't have time for this game.

40
00:08:57,870 --> 00:09:02,330
- Now leave before I call the police.
- Call them if you want.

41
00:09:02,408 --> 00:09:04,603
I'm sure they'd love to meet you.

42
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:09,809
Who are you?

43
00:09:09,882 --> 00:09:12,316
My name's Todd Bowden.

44
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:16,185
I didn't mean to scare you.
I just really wanna talk to you.

45
00:09:16,255 --> 00:09:19,691
It you could let me in
for a minute?

46
00:09:19,759 --> 00:09:23,354
Please, Mr. Dussander?

47
00:09:26,098 --> 00:09:27,030
<i>All of this...</i>

48
00:09:27,099 --> 00:09:31,263
because you saw an old man
with a raincoat and an umbrella?

49
00:09:31,337 --> 00:09:35,171
It wasn't that easy. I mean, these
pictures are 40 years old, at least.

50
00:09:35,241 --> 00:09:38,836
But when I held 'em up next to
the ones I took, I knew I was close.

51
00:09:38,911 --> 00:09:42,813
- You took photographs of me?
- Yeah.

52
00:09:42,882 --> 00:09:45,646
But even then,
I couldn't be sure.

53
00:09:45,718 --> 00:09:50,052
I needed real proof, so I dusted
your mailbox for fingerprints.

54
00:09:50,122 --> 00:09:53,353
You know, that's a lot
harder than people think.

55
00:09:53,426 --> 00:09:57,089
I had to go back to Toytown
three times to get all the stutf.

56
00:09:57,163 --> 00:09:59,097
Then I waited till
you were at the movies.

57
00:09:59,165 --> 00:10:02,794
You put dust on my mailbox
for fingerprints?

58
00:10:02,868 --> 00:10:05,803
You took photographs of me?
What else did you do?

59
00:10:06,939 --> 00:10:09,100
I already had a copy
of your fingerprints.

60
00:10:09,175 --> 00:10:11,405
They're on your want sheet
from the Israeli government.

61
00:10:11,477 --> 00:10:13,468
It's all on database
at U.C. Irvine.

62
00:10:17,717 --> 00:10:19,708
Are you okay?

63
00:10:22,555 --> 00:10:24,455
Would you care
for a drink, boy?

64
00:10:24,523 --> 00:10:26,821
- How about milk?
- Milk.

65
00:10:37,403 --> 00:10:40,998
You told your parents
about all this then?

66
00:10:41,073 --> 00:10:43,007
You think I'm crazy?

67
00:10:44,677 --> 00:10:48,477
It takes eight good matches
for a print to get accepted in court.

68
00:10:48,547 --> 00:10:50,105
They're called compares.

69
00:10:50,182 --> 00:10:54,380
One or two is not so hard to find, but
eight good ones, that's really tough.

70
00:10:54,453 --> 00:10:58,014
It all sounds
very exciting, boy...

71
00:10:58,090 --> 00:11:01,719
but I'm afraid all your work
has been for nothing.

72
00:11:01,794 --> 00:11:03,523
I found 14 compares.

73
00:11:08,768 --> 00:11:11,430
Boy, what you have done...

74
00:11:11,504 --> 00:11:15,964
I have to explain this to you because,
clearly, you don't understand.

75
00:11:16,042 --> 00:11:19,068
What you have done
is a violation.

76
00:11:19,145 --> 00:11:21,079
Like those experiments
with the decompression chamber.

77
00:11:21,147 --> 00:11:24,605
- Now, that's a violation.
- To hell with this and to hell with you.

78
00:11:24,684 --> 00:11:26,618
I'm calling the police.

79
00:11:26,686 --> 00:11:30,417
Your father will beat your behind when
he picks you up from the police station.

80
00:11:30,489 --> 00:11:33,947
- My parents don't believe in violence.
- They should start. I'm calling.

81
00:11:45,304 --> 00:11:47,238
My name is Denker.

82
00:11:51,444 --> 00:11:53,378
Arthur Denker.

83
00:11:56,048 --> 00:11:57,481
I'm an American.

84
00:11:58,951 --> 00:12:02,182
I became a citizen in 1955.

85
00:12:05,925 --> 00:12:07,859
I vote.

86
00:12:10,629 --> 00:12:15,828
You've no right to come here
and say these lies about me.

87
00:12:18,838 --> 00:12:20,806
I have your fingerprints.

88
00:12:21,774 --> 00:12:24,436
I have your photographs.

89
00:12:24,510 --> 00:12:27,138
One way or another,
I'll get them to the right people.

90
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:37,283
This is unforgivable.

91
00:12:42,528 --> 00:12:45,793
What do you want?
Tell me.

92
00:12:48,033 --> 00:12:51,730
- I wanna hear about it.
- Hear about what?

93
00:12:51,804 --> 00:12:54,238
The stories.

94
00:12:54,306 --> 00:12:55,739
Everything.

95
00:12:56,842 --> 00:12:58,537
What "everything"?

96
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:02,240
Everything they're afraid
to show us in school.

97
00:13:04,049 --> 00:13:05,482
You were there.

98
00:13:05,551 --> 00:13:08,019
You did those things.

99
00:13:08,087 --> 00:13:11,386
No one can tell it
better than you can.

100
00:13:11,457 --> 00:13:13,391
That's all I want.

101
00:13:13,459 --> 00:13:15,757
Then I'll leave you alone.

102
00:13:15,828 --> 00:13:18,228
And just so you know...

103
00:13:21,133 --> 00:13:24,193
everything I have on you...

104
00:13:24,270 --> 00:13:28,536
the compares, the want sheet,
all the photographs...

105
00:13:28,607 --> 00:13:30,802
are all in a very safe place.

106
00:13:30,876 --> 00:13:34,209
It anything happens to me,
someone will find it. Believe me.

107
00:13:37,416 --> 00:13:39,782
Tell me, boy...

108
00:13:39,852 --> 00:13:42,343
why should I consider
any of this?

109
00:13:42,421 --> 00:13:45,413
Because you hung up
the phone, that's why.

110
00:14:08,914 --> 00:14:11,610
Judging by the results
of your first exam...

111
00:14:11,684 --> 00:14:17,054
I think that for most of you, we moved
a little too tast through chapter one.

112
00:14:18,257 --> 00:14:20,521
By a show of hands...

113
00:14:20,593 --> 00:14:24,427
how many of you think you know
what sociology is?

114
00:14:26,665 --> 00:14:29,657
That's what I thought.

115
00:14:29,735 --> 00:14:32,670
All right, class.
Let's turn to chapter two.

116
00:14:40,980 --> 00:14:43,676
<i>Once they were in the chamber,</i>
<i>how long did it take?</i>

117
00:14:43,749 --> 00:14:45,273
<i>Five minutes?</i>

118
00:14:46,252 --> 00:14:48,914
<i>Gott, no.</i>
<i>The prussic acid...</i>

119
00:14:48,988 --> 00:14:51,115
took about l5 minutes.

120
00:14:51,190 --> 00:14:53,351
But the monoxide...

121
00:14:53,425 --> 00:14:56,986
could take an hour,
sometimes more.

122
00:14:57,830 --> 00:15:00,697
What happened to them?
I mean, exactly.

123
00:15:05,537 --> 00:15:08,131
It was a mess.

124
00:15:08,207 --> 00:15:10,607
They would lose control
of their bodies.

125
00:15:10,676 --> 00:15:16,046
They vomited, urinated
and defecated themselves.

126
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:20,711
Even though the gas came in
from the vents in the ceiling...

127
00:15:20,786 --> 00:15:23,277
they would climb
on top of each other...

128
00:15:23,355 --> 00:15:27,724
desperately reaching for
fresh air that wasn't there.

129
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:31,996
They died in a mountain
of themselves.

130
00:15:33,232 --> 00:15:35,792
What about the children?

131
00:15:37,803 --> 00:15:39,862
On the bottom.

132
00:15:42,741 --> 00:15:45,141
Did anyone ever survive it?

133
00:15:50,616 --> 00:15:52,550
One time...

134
00:15:54,386 --> 00:15:57,844
the gas didn't work.

135
00:15:57,923 --> 00:16:00,016
There was a leak in the pipes...

136
00:16:00,092 --> 00:16:03,858
so oxygen mixed with the monoxide.

137
00:16:05,297 --> 00:16:07,390
It was horrible.

138
00:16:07,466 --> 00:16:11,232
But after an hour
they were still moving...

139
00:16:11,303 --> 00:16:14,602
stumbling around the room
like drunks...

140
00:16:14,673 --> 00:16:16,607
their eyes glassy.

141
00:16:18,644 --> 00:16:19,906
What did you do?

142
00:16:21,380 --> 00:16:25,578
I ordered more gas,
but we didn't know about the leak.

143
00:16:25,651 --> 00:16:29,485
Soon they began
to twitch all over...

144
00:16:29,555 --> 00:16:31,489
like they were dancing.

145
00:16:31,557 --> 00:16:33,923
Some even tell
to their knees...

146
00:16:33,993 --> 00:16:38,589
laughing this terrible
high-pitched squeal.

147
00:16:39,565 --> 00:16:42,591
Even the guards were frightened.

148
00:16:46,005 --> 00:16:47,939
It didn't kill them.

149
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,100
After two hours...

150
00:16:50,175 --> 00:16:53,201
I sent tive men in with ritles.

151
00:16:58,217 --> 00:17:01,015
It's getting dark.
Your mother will be worried.

152
00:17:02,554 --> 00:17:04,488
Oh, shit! I gotta go.

153
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:07,753
I can be here tomorrow by 3:15.
I want to hear the end of this.

154
00:17:07,826 --> 00:17:09,760
The end?

155
00:17:13,966 --> 00:17:15,900
The end.

156
00:18:13,392 --> 00:18:14,416
Todd?

157
00:18:14,493 --> 00:18:15,960
Are you up?

158
00:18:16,028 --> 00:18:18,496
Honey, let's go.
Joey's outside.

159
00:18:18,564 --> 00:18:21,032
Tell him I'm comin',
will you?

160
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:23,034
You said you were up
halt an hour ago.

161
00:18:27,106 --> 00:18:29,666
Yeah, I must have
tallen back asleep.

162
00:18:29,741 --> 00:18:32,710
Listen, honey, I'm gonna
see a client tonight at 7:00.

163
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:35,303
But I've got some cold chicken
in the tridge and plenty of...

164
00:18:35,380 --> 00:18:38,577
It's okay. I'm gonna eat
over at Mr. Denker's house.

165
00:18:39,985 --> 00:18:42,579
What are you gonna do
all night? Watch TV?

166
00:18:42,654 --> 00:18:45,885
Mom, I told you. He doesn't watch TV.
I read books to him.

167
00:18:45,958 --> 00:18:47,789
Will you not worry about it?

168
00:18:47,860 --> 00:18:50,351
Listen to me. I want you
to invite him over here...

169
00:18:50,429 --> 00:18:53,523
because Daddy and I
still want to meet him.

170
00:18:53,599 --> 00:18:55,760
Okay?

171
00:18:55,834 --> 00:18:57,768
<i>So the policeman said to me...</i>

172
00:18:57,836 --> 00:19:02,671
"Mr. Denker, if you can't see the road,
you shouldn't be driving.

173
00:19:02,741 --> 00:19:06,006
Now, how many tingers
am I holding up?"

174
00:19:06,078 --> 00:19:08,171
And I said,
"Well now, officer.

175
00:19:08,247 --> 00:19:10,613
Let me guess.

176
00:19:10,682 --> 00:19:12,115
One?"

177
00:19:16,088 --> 00:19:18,022
That was the end of
my driving in America.

178
00:19:18,924 --> 00:19:21,552
I've taken the bus ever since.

179
00:19:21,627 --> 00:19:26,030
Well, of course, I'm not drivin'
much either with this wheelchair...

180
00:19:26,098 --> 00:19:29,067
but my eyesight is not
what it used to be.

181
00:19:30,802 --> 00:19:33,100
That's a whitetail buck.

182
00:19:35,274 --> 00:19:37,742
That's a remnant
trom our life in Carolina.

183
00:19:37,809 --> 00:19:40,209
Dick brought that down
in the Yadkin River...

184
00:19:40,279 --> 00:19:42,509
- seven or eight years ago.
- Seven.

185
00:19:42,581 --> 00:19:46,540
You know, your grandson never told me
that he came trom a family of hunters.

186
00:19:46,618 --> 00:19:49,610
Oh, Todd never took
a shine to guns.

187
00:19:49,688 --> 00:19:53,556
- He's good at other things.
- Baseball is Todd's game.

188
00:19:53,625 --> 00:19:56,617
- Arthur, sure you don't want a cigar?
- No, thank you.

189
00:19:56,695 --> 00:20:00,654
It you don't mind, I'll have one
of my cigarettes. Where are they?

190
00:20:00,732 --> 00:20:03,667
Ah! Let me help you
with that, Arthur.

191
00:20:03,735 --> 00:20:05,635
My dear...

192
00:20:05,704 --> 00:20:09,333
your generosity humbles me.

193
00:20:09,408 --> 00:20:13,003
I thank you for
a most enchanting evening.

194
00:20:14,179 --> 00:20:15,612
Well.

195
00:20:17,916 --> 00:20:21,010
I wonder it you'd mind
it I asked you a personal question?

196
00:20:21,086 --> 00:20:22,917
Not at all.

197
00:20:22,988 --> 00:20:25,650
What'd you do during the war?

198
00:20:31,363 --> 00:20:35,424
I was in the reserves,
as were most young men, Victor.

199
00:20:35,500 --> 00:20:39,664
But then, my poor eyesight
kept me out of combat, I thank God.

200
00:20:39,738 --> 00:20:43,572
No, I spent most of the war
in the military hospital...

201
00:20:43,642 --> 00:20:47,100
washing bed linens
and nurses' unitorms.

202
00:20:51,350 --> 00:20:53,147
You've been
pretty quiet tonight.

203
00:20:54,253 --> 00:20:58,485
I'm sorry. It's just that I've heard
all of these stories before.

204
00:20:59,558 --> 00:21:02,254
That's all right, my dear.
The boy's just being honest.

205
00:21:02,327 --> 00:21:04,158
It's a privilege of boys.

206
00:21:05,764 --> 00:21:10,531
A privilege that men
must sometimes give up.

207
00:21:13,138 --> 00:21:16,665
You know, that reminds me. I...

208
00:21:16,742 --> 00:21:20,473
It must have been my tirst year
at the university.

209
00:21:20,545 --> 00:21:24,447
There was a group of about three
or tour of us, and we dropped in and...

210
00:21:24,516 --> 00:21:29,419
<i>At first my men took turns shooting them</i>
<i>in the head, but there were so many.</i>

211
00:21:29,488 --> 00:21:33,083
<i>Two or three bodies could</i>
<i>be packed into each oven.</i>

212
00:21:33,158 --> 00:21:36,650
<i>They were ground into fine ash.</i>

213
00:21:36,728 --> 00:21:40,858
<i>A whole town was wiped off</i>
<i>the face of the earth.</i>

214
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:57,915
<i>And still,</i>
<i>it wasn't enough for Himmler.</i>

215
00:21:57,983 --> 00:21:59,712
<i>That was a dark year.</i>

216
00:21:59,785 --> 00:22:04,813
<i>We ordered every Jew in Kiev</i>
<i>to come to the Babi Yar Ravine.</i>

217
00:22:04,890 --> 00:22:09,884
<i>You must remember, boy, the '20s</i>
<i>were a desperate time in Germany.</i>

218
00:22:09,961 --> 00:22:12,623
<i>The Treaty of Versailles</i>
<i>had left us crippled.</i>

219
00:22:12,698 --> 00:22:15,258
<i>God, we must have</i>...
<i>They would hide</i>...

220
00:22:15,334 --> 00:22:19,862
<i>The shooting-- The walls-- The sewers--</i>
<i>But we always found them.</i>

221
00:22:19,938 --> 00:22:23,874
<i>If the dogs didn't,</i>
<i>the smoke and fire would.</i>

222
00:22:23,942 --> 00:22:28,345
<i>We would round them up</i>
<i>and march them out to a large pit.</i>

223
00:22:28,413 --> 00:22:31,041
<i>At the time, the shooting</i>
<i>was no longer killing.</i>

224
00:22:31,116 --> 00:22:35,985
<i>Nothing could stop the killing.</i>
<i>It was no longer death.</i>

225
00:22:36,054 --> 00:22:40,548
<i>I will never forget</i>
<i>the sound that night.</i>

226
00:22:40,625 --> 00:22:44,686
So many of them on top
of each other like that.

227
00:22:44,763 --> 00:22:48,290
After a few hours,
they began to settle.

228
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:56,072
A head would fall.

229
00:22:56,141 --> 00:22:59,599
Yeah, an arm would drop.

230
00:23:03,815 --> 00:23:07,751
It was a bit like
the sound of blowing leaves.

231
00:23:11,323 --> 00:23:14,190
What did it teel like?

232
00:23:27,706 --> 00:23:29,640
It was something
that had to be done.

233
00:23:29,708 --> 00:23:33,439
A door had been opened
and couldn't be shut.

234
00:23:33,512 --> 00:23:35,446
It was the end...

235
00:23:36,948 --> 00:23:39,041
You don't understand.

236
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:44,547
<i>You've done it a million times!</i>
<i>Let's go!</i>

237
00:24:05,076 --> 00:24:07,442
